@node "Document_0" "Introduction"
@{b}
  ##

 ###
  ##                            @{fg shine}Introduction@{fg text}
  ##
  ##
 ####
@{ub}
Action is a program which performs certain action on file, depending on it's
filetype. Similar programs already exist, but none has all advantages of
Action:

@{fg shine}->@{fg text} Supports FileID.library, recognising 645 filetypes, and even more
additional filetypes could be added.
@{fg shine}->@{fg text} However, such large number of filetypes is no headache for configuring,
because they are aliased into several groups...
@{fg shine}->@{fg text} Unlimited number of actions could be defined. View, Edit and Identify are
included in distribution.
@{fg shine}->@{fg text} Easy to configure with font-sensitive prefs GUI.
@{fg shine}->@{fg text} Filetypes could be forced (f.e. if you want to view html file as text or
picture as hex data).

Benefits of using Action:

@{fg shine}->@{fg text} You can configure every program which requires external viewer only once,
and forget about it. Guide on how to configure ToolManager, DOpus4 and MIME -
compliant programs to use Action is in @{"Usage" link "Document_3"} section of this guide.
@{fg shine}->@{fg text} If you change program you are using for viewing/editing some filetype, now
you should apply that change in ActionPrefs only, not in every program which
had used it!
@{fg shine}->@{fg text} You don't need to think about viewer/editor names, paths and arguments
when working in Shell.

If you are not sure could Action be useful to you, there is Test Action
script in Action archive, which can make neccesary arrangements for you to
test Action, without any permanent changes to your system.

@endnode
@node "Document_1" "Installation"
@{b}
############
#|        |#
#| Action |#
#|________|#                    @{fg shine}Installation@{fg text}
#          #
#  [TŻŻ]   #
\\###########
@{ub}
@{fg shine}Automatic:@{fg text}

Double click on @{b}Install Action@{ub} icon, then follow the instructions.

@{fg shine}Manual:@{fg text}

Copy Action         to C:
Copy Invoker        to C:
Copy ActionPrefs#?  to SYS:Prefs/
Makedir                ENVARC:Action
Copy View           to ENVARC:Action
Copy Edit           to ENVARC:Action
Copy Identify       to ENVARC:Action
Copy Action.guide#? to wherewer:you/want
Copy Gui.Library    to LIBS:
Copy FileID.library to LIBS:

@endnode
@node "Document_2" "Setup"
@{b}
 #####
##   ##
     ##
    ##                             @{fg shine}Setup@{fg text}
   ##

   ##
@{ub}
@{"With ActionPrefs" link "" 12} @{"Manualy" link "" 43} @{"Notes" link "" 64}

@{fg shine}With ActionPrefs:@{fg text}

Action could be fully configured with ActionPrefs. It's use is pretty
straightforward, so I think that no details are realy needed. Here is a quick
guide about using it.

First, you should click on top left listview and select action that you want
to edit. Note that it is possible to edit only one action at a time!

When all filetypes are loaded, you can click on filetype you want to edit.
You can also search for desired filetype. String gadgets at the right side
are now filled with informations about selected filetype.

Now you can change filetype description, alias and action. Filetype
description doesn't affect way Action work, only what is shown in
ActionPrefs. Alias is a name of filetype whose settings will be used if no
action is defined for selected filetype. Action is a program which will be
executed when action is performed on a certain filetype. You should always
use it's full path! Filename that will be passed as an argument is entered
as "%s" (it would work without the quotes, but not for files which have space
in name).

It is not possible to change name of filetype, only to delete it and Add a
new one! About naming filetypes, see @{"notes" link "" 64}.

At last, you can click on Use to test your settings, or on Save to store them
permanently. You can also Quit without saving them if you don't like them.

Pressing on the Create Invoker button will (immediately) create a link  to
C:Invoker for selected action.

@{fg shine}Manualy:@{fg text}

Action's configuration files are stored in directory @{b}ENV:Action/@{ub} . Each
config file has definitions for action which is same as it's name. For
example, @{b}ENV:Action/View@{ub} stores configuration which will be loaded if you
type @{b}Action view filename@{ub} in shell.

Configuration files are pure ASCII text files, containing one line of data
for every filetype, following the template @{b}TYPE/A,DESC/A,ALIAS/K,ACTION/F@{ub}.
That means, that every line must contain name of the filetype and it's
description, and that it can contain keyword ALIAS, followed by a name of
aliased filetype, and that any of them must have quotes if it contains space,
except for the last one. Examples:

Unknown		"Unknown file"		MultiView "%s"
Bootblock	"Amiga bootblock"	ALIAS HEX
019		"IFF ILBM picture/brush"	ALIAS Picture	PPShow >NIL: "%s"
.txt		"ASCII text"		ALIAS Text		HD1:More "%s"
text/html	"HTML document"		ALIAS 641

Parts of line can be separated with space or tab, I prefer tab, and that is
output of ActionPrefs. Last line @{b}must@{ub} be empty.

@{fg shine}Notes:@{fg text}

It is possible to configure Action in a way which would cause unwanted
behaviour. See note about @{"bugs" link "Document_6" 14}.

Names of filetypes should not be numbers (as theese are used for filetypes of
FileID.library). If name of a filetype starts with point @{b}.@{ub}, it will
be used as a new filetype, for files which have same extension as name of
filetype. Otherwise, it could only be used with Alias or by forcing it.

@endnode
@node "Document_3" "Usage"
@{b}
Couldn't
 think
   of                               @{fg shine}Usage@{fg text}
   a
picture
@{ub}
@{"From CLI" link "" 10} @{"From Workbench" link "" 23} @{"Via Invoker" link "" 29} @{"With DOpus4" link "" 46} @{"With ToolManager" link "" 68} @{"With MIME" link "" 81}

@{fg shine}From CLI:@{fg text}

Command template for Action is: @{b}ACTION/A,FILENAME/A,AS/K@{ub}. It means
that, in CLI, you must provide Action with an action to perform, and with
filename on which that action will be performed, and that you can add AS
switch for forcing of filetype. Examples:

Action View index.html		- will load index.html in a web browser
Action view index.html AS .txt	- will load index.html in a text viewer
Action EDIT index.html		- will load index.html in a HTML editor
Action edit index.html as .txt	- will load index.html in a text editor
Action EdIt index.html as HEX	- will load index.html in a hex editor

@{fg shine}From Workbench:@{fg text}

It is not possible to use Action from Workbench. It might be possible if I
receive enoguh requests... However, there is no need for it, because it could
be used via Invoker:

@{fg shine}Via Invoker:@{fg text}

Invoker is a program which invokes Action, multiple times if neccesary, to
perform an action on a number on files. Action which will be performed is
same as name of Invoker, for example, if you rename Invoker to @{b}View@{ub},
using it will produce same results as @{b}Action View@{ub}. Of course, you
can have several copies (or links) of Invoker with diferent names, for every
Action you need.

Invoker could be used from CLI or from Workbench.  For instance, if you have
renamed it to @{b}View@{ub}, in CLI, just type:  @{b}View file1 file2 file3 ...@{ub}
and it will execute @{b}Action View@{ub} for every file; in Workbench, you
can simply set tooltype of some icon to @{b}View@{ub}, and it will execute
@{b}Action View@{ub} with file which has that icon. If you give Invoker an
icon, it will start Action for every file which is selected when Invoker's
icon is double - clicked.

@{fg shine}With DOpus4:@{fg text}

Start ConfigOpus, and click on @{b}Filetypes@{ub} gadget. Now you can @{b}Delete@{ub}
every filetype action which Action can recognise, which would probably be
every filetype action, except DEFAULT, and actions where some @{b}Event@{ub}
Action can't support is defined (unpacking archives with Click-m-click, for
example). In every remaining filetype actions you should delete all Command
events and Double-click event.

Now, select DEFAULT action. For Double-click action you should click on an
entry, or if there are no entries, on New entry, set it's type to @{b}AmigaDOS@{ub},
and enter @{b}Action View {f}@{ub} in string gadget. Then you should select
Do all files @{b}flag@{ub}, and your job is finished.

Now you can repeat above steps for every Command, except that for HexRead you
should enter @{b}Action View {f} AS HEX@{ub} in string gadget, and for Read you should
enter @{b}Action View {f} AS Text@{ub}, etc. You can also repeat above steps for any
filetypes you have left besides DEFAULT.

When everything is done, click on @{b}Okay@{ub}, @{b}Okay@{ub} and @{b}Okay@{ub}. If you are satisfied,
go back to ConfigOpus and click on @{b}Save@{ub}.

@{fg shine}With ToolManager:@{fg text}

In ToolManager Preferences, click on @{b}@{u}N@{uu}ew Object@{ub} button.

Enter @{b}Name@{ub} of action, set @{b}@{u}E@{uu}xec type@{ub} to @{b}Workbench@{ub}, enter name of Invoker
copy you want to be started when that exec type is called, and enter
directory where that Invoker copy is in as @{b}Current Directory@{ub}. @{b}@{u}A@{uu}rguments@{ub}
checkmark should be turned on. After everything is done, click on @{b}@{u}U@{uu}se@{ub}.
Now you can use your Exec object with Meny, Icon or Dock objects.

It is possible to configure ToolManager to call Action directly, but it
wouldn't work for multiple files!

@{fg shine}With MIME:@{fg text}

In every program that relies on MIME, for every MIME type you need to
display, simply enter

@{b}Action View %s AS mime/type@{ub}

for example:

@{b}text/html@{ub} | @{b}Action View %s AS text/html@{ub}

If you need MIME type that is currently not supported, you can add it in
ActionPrefs. If you think that it should be supported, mail me, and I'll
probably include it into next distribution. Of course, MIME types doesn't
need to be forced, but assumption is that program which called Action knows
better...

@endnode
