@node "Document_10" "GiftWare"
@{b}    
         \@
  ,·····\@\@\@
,:....,· \@
:     :  :                        @{fg shine}GiftWare@{fg text}
:     : ,'
:.....:·
@{ub}
Action is a giftware program.

It means that, if you use it regurarely, you are obliged to send a gift to
the @{"author" link "Document_7"}. A gift could be simply a postcard, or it could be something
bigger. It doesn't need to have real value - only your effort is important.
However, money is accepted as a gift. Emails doesn't count as gifts, except
if they contain useful sugestions, bugreports, or something which would go
into next release :)

Everyone who has already sent me a gift for my giftware program, or an email
for my emailware program, doesn't need to do that again. Hi, Jen! ;)

@endnode
@node "Document_11" "Distribution"
@{b}
##########__
########### \\
#############                   @{fg shine}Distribution@{fg text}
#############
(_)(_)   (_)
@{ub}
Action is a @{"giftware" link "Document_10"} program, and, as such, you can freely distribute it,
providing that all files in it's archive are left intact. You can @{b}not@{ub}
distribute Action, Invoker, ActionPrefs, this guide, or any other file from
this archive separately from other files.

You can put it on public domain disk or include it in public domain disk
library, @{b}only@{ub} if you do not charge it with too high copying fee.

You can put it on a PD software compilation (such as Aminet CD), or magazine
coverdisk, @{b}only@{ub} if you send a note to the @{"author" link "Document_7"} stating that you
have done it. You don't need author's permission, nor reply.

You can include it in commercial package or commercial program collection, 
@{b}only@{ub} with a written permission from the @{"author" link "Document_7"}.

@endnode
